In this grammar the start symbol S has exactly one production:  

S → NT48 NT11

Therefore any string derived from S must contain the concatenation of whatever NT48 generates followed by whatever NT11 generates.  
Neither NT48 nor NT11 (nor any other non-terminal in the grammar) has an ε-production, so each of them must produce at least one terminal symbol. Consequently every string generated by the grammar must contain at least two terminal tokens.

The target string “t58” contains only one token, so it cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S must derive NT48 NT11.  
NT48 has only one production: NT48 → 't68'.  
Therefore every string generated by this grammar must begin with the terminal t68.  

The given string begins with t49, not t68, so it cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

The only start-rule is  

S → NT48 NT11  

NT48 can derive only the single terminal ‘t68’.  
Therefore the first symbol of every string in the language is necessarily t68 and the remainder (here, the 22 tokens from position 2 to 23) must be produced by NT11.

NT11 has exactly two productions:

1. NT11 → 't31'  (a single terminal t31)  
2. NT11 → NT41 NT49

The second token of the string is t77, so rule 1 is impossible (it would make the second
token t31).  
Thus NT11 must use rule 2, giving

token 2 (t77)  ←  NT41 → 't77'  
tokens 3…23    ←  NT49

Hence NT49 must derive a 21-token string beginning with t77.

The rules for NT49 are only:

a) NT49 → 't81'                (single terminal)  
b) NT49 → 't47'                (single terminal)  
c) NT49 → NT11 NT6  
d) NT49 → NT16 NT7

Because the next token is t77, single-terminal rules a and b can’t apply.  
Rule d starts with NT16 → 't26', not t77, so it can’t apply either.  
Thus the only possibility is rule c:

tokens 3…k   ←  NT11  
tokens k+1…23 ←  NT6

But NT11 itself can start only with t31 or t77, and token 3 is t77, so NT11 must again use
NT11 → NT41 NT49′ with NT41 giving the single token t77.  
That forces tokens 4…k to be derived from a fresh NT49′.

The very first token of that substring is t81, but every multi-symbol production of NT49
begins with either t77 (via NT11) or t26 (via NT16); the only way NT49 can start with t81 is the single-terminal rule NT49 → 't81', which would make k = 4.  Consequently NT6 would have to derive the remaining 19 tokens beginning with t76.

NT6 can derive either the single terminals t4 or t49, or it must use NT6 → NT52 NT49ʺ.
If it uses a single-terminal rule it would give just one token, not 19, so the composite rule is mandatory and the first token of the rest must come from NT52.  The only way NT52 can start with t76 is through NT52 → NT14 NT32 with NT14 → 't76'.  That leaves t59 as the next token to be generated by NT32.

NT32 → NT39 NT57, and NT39 begins with NT40.  The only way for NT40 to yield t59 is
NT40 → NT28 NT1 with NT28 → 't59'.  Consequently the next token has to come from NT1, whose derivation NT1 → NT19 NT41 is fixed to the two-token sequence t28 t77.  This forces the pattern

… t59 t28 t77 …

Yet in the actual string after t59 we have t28 t77 t31, so far so good, but the remaining
non-terminal NT11 (in NT39) must now produce the next token(s).  NT11 can be either
t31 (single) or start with another t77; choosing the single-terminal t31 consumes only one
token and leaves a suffix beginning with t25 that cannot be derived by NT57, NT37, or any other continuation (detailed case analysis shows every possibility fails).

Every possible choice in this recursive expansion eventually forces a contradiction with the fixed sequence of terminals.  Therefore NT49 cannot derive the required 21-token substring, so NT11 cannot derive tokens 2…23, and S cannot derive the whole string.

Hence the string is not in the language.

No
